{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17539550","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17539550"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:43:09+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:43:09+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16668"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16668","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16668"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.12,0.1,0.16,0.6,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9359"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109065"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9359","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9359"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16668"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91432"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"10"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"2936"},{"type":"tags","id":"2982"},{"type":"tags","id":"3033"},{"type":"tags","id":"3163"},{"type":"tags","id":"3237"},{"type":"tags","id":"3275"},{"type":"tags","id":"12914"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22154"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25038"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40634"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109065","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/109065"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department accompanied by her partner with behavioural changes over the past five days. Her partner reports she has been sleeping two hours per night and has spent $12,000 on multiple online business ventures. She has bipolar affective disorder but no other medical conditions. She usually takes sodium valproate but stopped this three weeks ago stating she \u0027felt cured\u0027.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well-groomed but restless. Her pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 135/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. When asked about her recent activities, she responds rapidly: \u0027I\u0027ve been researching cryptocurrency investments because blockchain will revolutionise healthcare delivery which reminds me I need to finish my medical degree online while developing an app for mindfulness meditation that uses artificial intelligence to predict stock market trends and I\u0027ve already hired developers in Silicon Valley but first I need to patent my theory about dark matter solving world hunger.\u0027\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes this patient\u0027s thought pattern?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Loosening of associations","Derailment","Tangentiality","Flight of ideas","Circumstantiality"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis case presents a complex differentiation between various formal thought disorders in the context of mania. The patient\u0027s speech demonstrates \u003Cstrong\u003Eflight of ideas\u003C/strong\u003E, characterised by rapid progression between topics that maintain tenuous but traceable connections (cryptocurrency \u2192 healthcare \u2192 medical degree \u2192 app development \u2192 artificial intelligence \u2192 patents). While racing and grandiose, the ideas follow a pattern that can be mapped, albeit with increasingly distant associations.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELoosening of associations\u003C/strong\u003E represents a more severe thought disorder where connections between ideas are completely absent or illogical. Unlike flight of ideas, where some thread of connection can be traced, loosening of associations would show no discernible link between concepts.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETangentiality\u003C/strong\u003E describes responses that begin on track but veer off onto an unrelated tangent, never returning to the original point. While the patient\u0027s speech shows tangential elements, the predominant pattern is the rapid progression through multiple loosely connected ideas rather than a single tangential departure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDerailment\u003C/strong\u003E refers to a gradual or sudden deviation from the train of thought, where ideas slip off track in an often subtle way. This differs from flight of ideas where the connections, though distant, remain identifiable.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECircumstantiality\u003C/strong\u003E involves indirect, over-detailed speech that eventually returns to the original point. While detailed, it maintains a single thread of thought rather than jumping between multiple ideas.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe presence of pressured speech, decreased need for sleep, excessive spending, and grandiose plans, combined with recent cessation of mood stabilisers, strongly suggests a manic episode. Flight of ideas is a characteristic feature of mania, reflecting the racing thoughts and distractibility typical of this phase of bipolar affective disorder.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Flight of ideas must be distinguished from other formal thought disorders through careful analysis of speech patterns and logical connections.","The combination of pressured speech, reduced need for sleep, and grandiose plans strongly suggests mania.","Recent cessation of mood stabilisers is a common precipitant of manic relapse."],"references":["Matorin AA, Avellaneda Ojeda AA, Shah AA, Ruiz P. Clinical manifestations of psychiatric disorders. In: Boland RC, Verduin ML, editors. Kaplan \u0026 Sadock\u2019s Comprehensive Textbook of Psychiatry. 11th ed. Philadelphia: Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2024. Chapter\u00a08.","Jeyasingam N. Flight of ideas\u2013death of a definition: a discussion on phenomenology. The Psychiatrist. 2013 Nov;37(11):359-62."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91432"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16668"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91432","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/91432"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-16T19:55:24+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-16T19:56:24+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9359"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109065"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"10","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/10"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udfad","name":"Psychiatry","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:46+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"